EXPLANATION – Matter in bolded italics is new; matter between brackets [omitted material] is material to be omitted.
AN ACT relating to public employees; requiring the Governor to include certain
information relating to collective bargaining agreements in the biennial
proposed executive budget; revising certain deadlines relating to the
negotiation, mediation and arbitration of collective bargaining
agreements with the Executive Department of the State Government;
making appropriations; and providing other matters properly relating
thereto.
Legislative Counsel’s Digest:
1 Under existing law, the Governor may, notwithstanding the provisions of any collective
2 bargaining agreement, include in the biennial proposed executive budget of the State any
3 amount of money the Governor deems appropriate for salaries, wage rates or any other form
4 of direct monetary compensation for employees. (NRS 288.510) Section 1 of this bill requires
5 the Governor, to the extent practicable, to include in the biennial proposed executive budget,
6 any amount of money to be paid as agreed upon in a collective bargaining agreement. Section
7 1 also requires that if the Governor determines it is impracticable to include such money in the
8 biennial proposed executive budget, he or she must submit a report stating the reason for such
9 a determination to the Legislature on the same day the budget is submitted.
10 Under existing law, certain groups of employees in the classified service of the Executive
11 Department of State Government are authorized to engage in collective bargaining with the
12 Executive Department concerning wages, hours and other terms and conditions of
13 employment for such employees. (NRS 288.400-288.630) In general, a collective bargaining
14 agreement for such a group of employees must begin on July 1 of an odd-numbered year and
15 must end on June 30 of the next odd-numbered year. (NRS 288.550)
16 Under existing law, the Governor is required to designate a representative to conduct
17 negotiations concerning collective bargaining agreements on behalf of the Executive
18 Department and negotiations between the representative of the Executive Department and the
19 exclusive representative of a bargaining unit are required to begin within 60 days after one
20 party notifies the other party of the desire to negotiate or on or before October 1 of each even-
21 numbered year, whichever is earlier. (NRS 288.565) Section 1.5 of this bill requires such
22 negotiations to begin: (1) on or before April 1, rather than October 1, of each even-numbered
23 year; and (2) within 60 days after an exclusive representative is designated for an
24 unrepresented bargaining unit.
25 Under existing law, either the representative of the Executive Department or the exclusive
26 representative of a bargaining unit are authorized to request a mediator if the parties do not

